text:
I honestly don't get why you're getting so much hate from a specific number of people complaining about the entire group of Vtuber English Hololivers, seriously, it's a truly tremendous feat to learn English in both its written and spoken variations for non-native speakers of said language, really. 0_0  Regardless, you have my full 100% support Gura, honestly. ^-^  

I also thought i'd add a suggestion on what you can stream in the future.  If you could, can you stream Underhell?  It's a Half-Life 2 mod story that has REALLY gotten a good-yet-obscure fanbase as well as a good development record as well.  It is literally 100%-free, all it takes is downloading the Source SDK Base 2007 (which is also 100% free) installed on Steam in order to run, then downloading the mod itself and then putting it in its proper directory, usually in the "sourcemods" folder located in "SteamApps" directory in the main Steam directory.  

The first chapter is the "Prologue" chapter which is mostly action-based, but the next chapter, titled "Chapter 1 Welcome to Underhell" is horror-action-based, that also utilizes stealth as well, especially in the later chapters, which I HIGHLY recommend you do, as well as gather all 52 cards.  You'll know that you've acquired all cards in a specific area since a text like "I believe I have found every card in the High Security Block..." for example, will show when you've acquired all cards in a specific area.  Here's where you can get the mod: moddb.com/mods/Underhell/downloads/Underhell-chapter-1 

And here's a list on all 52 cards locations that are segmented in areas they're located in:  underhellmod.fandom.com/wiki/Card  (Getting cards unlocks VERY handy rewards as demonstrated in the first showcase video of the two made by the developers themselves: part 1:  youtube.com/watch?v=UZdDR6nwLY8   part 2:  youtube.com/watch?v=lkhBvLxutLU ) Also, save the High Security Block power room for the last one to do, for a very specific reason of which I won't spoil, just be sure to follow what I said. ^^;

There's also the House that acts as the "hub" of the mod, but BE WARNED...  staying up at night hours runs the risk of incurring Her dreaded wrath, making for a VERY potent scare-fest, especially a specific "phone call"... (which, unfortunately, can also be encountered during the "usually"-safe daytime hours) heh heh heh... >:D So yeah, be VERY wary during both times of the day, ESPECIALLY the night time hours at the House... So yeah, there's PLENTY of scares for a potential first-timer like yourself, and it is an FPS and it seems you've streamed one already, and i'm sure you'll love this one as well. text:
¬†@billbard887¬† If I may add a bit to this discussion without antagonizing you,  Gura's career as a Vtuber is barely beginning, but she has shown appreciation and commitment to the fans of Hololive. It seems you may be a bit new, but Hololive is an agency that signs contracts with these Vtubers. Essentially, what this means is that Gura is coming into a decently-sized company that already has a strong fanbase. 

Although from an outsider's perspective it may seem that she has gotten attention for nothing more than being cute, when placed into context, she actually has the pressure of continuing the company's legacy as apart of the next generation of Vtubers. Moreover, this pressure is compounded by the fact that she is of the first English-speaking Vtubers to be contracted under this company.

This alone warrants the pre-existing fans of Hololive, especially the English-speaking ones, to show as much support as possible to bridge the gap between these two intermingling cultures. However, the aforementioned wholesomeness, talent, and, yes, cuteness, of Gura (and the rest of HololiveEN) does well to encourage the fans to share the love they have for Hololive's other branches with this next generation.

 In short, Gura is coming into a scene that is abundant with talent, so much so that the pre-existing fans, as a part of a warm, welcoming community, express their excitement for her future efforts as soon as she is monetized. Make no mistake, some of these people could very well fall under the term "simp" (although more fall under "Shrimp"), but to insult someone for receiving support, especially someone who expresses their immense appreciation for these kind donators, and place them on the same level as Twitch Thots with "Tier 3 Simps" and "low effort content" is incredibly disrespectful. 

I can very well understand if this content isn't for you; I get it if you actively dislike Vtubers. However, spreading this toxicity, in a place where the community is tight-knit and care about these Vtubers, not only for the cute anime characters, nor the voices, but for the people behind them and the lives they lead, will only get you attacked. Look anywhere in Hololive and you will see the genuine care and massive amounts of effort these girls commit to their jobs and their fans, as well as the reciprocation of this love received by the community.

Her fans are not mindless simps, we come to Vtubers to get away from those kinds of people and the content-creators attached. We come here to have fun and find a genuine reason to smile for a day. If you give it a chance, we wouldn't mind welcoming you into the community as well. Have a good day.

text:
¬†@billbard887¬† I see. I understand where you are coming from, and I have seen some people spend excessive amounts of money (I've seen one person spend over $1,000.) on these streams as well. This would make it seem like these people expect something more from these streamers, but I can't, nor should, judge everyone who donates when I don't know them or their socioeconomic status personally. I could very easily make the argument that "it's their money and they can do what they want," but I understand the sentiment that not everyone is a responsible spender as well. 

However, I can argue that these girls do put a lot work into their content. If you would allow me to digress from Gura for a bit, Vtubers under Hololive are known as "Talents," and for good reason. Their talents are often a product of hobbies, but that doesn't negate the effort they put in to be, and stay consistently, relevant, humble, and, above all, entertaining. Take Ina's (another HololiveEN member) drawing skills for example, she didn't begin drawing at an early age so she could do so on stream as a Vtuber, but that also shouldn't mean that her drawing streams are low effort. 

Touching on the original Japanese branch of Hololive for a moment:

- Inugami Korone frequently does 8 hour endurance streams. If you jump in during the first and last 10 minutes, you will see that she keeps the same level of excitement in order to continue being entertaining and have fun with her audience.

-Hoshimachi Suisei has an amazing voice, is an incredibly talented artist, and is a god at Tetris.

-Kyru Coco was the first bilingual Hololive member to bridge the gap between Japanese and English audiences. She worked hard to stay entertaining and push the limits of her content, so much so that her streams were banned by Youtube for some time. Yet, she went on to work twice as hard to maintain her fanbase, even breaking and crying in her return stream over her fear of losing her fans and friends in Hololive. 

These are only very few examples, but the general trend of Hololive shows that they themselves are talented at finding great human beings that put a lot of effort and care into this craft. And this is without even mentioning the 3D concerts, Superchat Reading Streams, original songs, art, collaborations, interviews, etc. that the girls themselves set up for the fans. I would never be able to give you an estimate on how much work being a Vtuber is, but watching enough of this content will convey the pressure of debuting without knowing whether fans will like you, stress of maintaining a streaming schedule and then changing said schedule to accommodate foreign fans, and anxiety associated with maintaining that audience and being consistently entertaining.

All this to say, Hololive has a good track record of hiring hardworking, talented, and humble individuals, and Gura is showing no signs of being an exception to that trend. Viewing Gura as an individual streamer, yeah, she hasn't done really much of anything, but seeing her in the context of the company's legacy, her success is very much predetermined and her hard work is already being rewarded in advance.
